ntity in the face of colonial pressures to assimilate and disappear. Drawing on rich oral, archival, material, visual, and quantitative evidence, Shirts Powdered Red tells the story of how Haudenosaunee people worked to maintain their nations' cultural and political sovereignty through selective engagement with trade and the rhetoric of civility, even as Haudenosaunee clothing and gendered labor increasingly became the focus of colonial conversion efforts throughout the upheavals and dispossession of the nineteenth century. Shirts Powdered Red offers a sweeping, detailed cultural history of three centuries of Haudenosaunee women's labor and agency to shape their nations' future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aClothing and dressxPolitical aspectszNew York (State)xHistory. 0aClothing and dressxPolitical aspectszQuébec (Province)xHistory. 0aClothing and dressxSymbolic aspectszNew York (State)xHistory. 0aClothing and dressxSymbolic aspectszQuébec (Province)xHistory. 0aIroquois IndiansxClothingxHistory. 0aIroquois IndiansxCommercexHistory. 0aIroquois IndiansxEthnic identityxHistory. 0aIroquois womenxSocial conditionsy17th century. 0aIroquois womenxSocial conditionsy18th century. 0aIroquois womenxSocial conditionsy19th century. 4aGender Studies. 4aNative American Studies. 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh  airoquois in the american revolution, women and the fur trade, iroquois clan matrons, iroquois clothing, haudenosaunee women, haudenosaunee clothing.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176789040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501767890423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501767890/original  a978-3-11-075183-3  Cornell Uni